## The Tea

On the eve of my twentieth year in those walls, an old woman came to me.

I had seen her before, in the way you see someone in a city you pass every day but never speak to. She cleaned the floors. She was invisible to the priests and the cardinals. They looked through her the way they looked through the stained glass—she was part of the architecture.

But that night she appeared at the door of my cell. She had no name I could pronounce. She carried a cup that smelled of earth and rot and something older than both.

"You have been here twenty years," she said. Her voice was not old. It was ageless. "You have learned what can be learned from books and silence. Now you must learn what cannot be learned."

"I have learned that we do not know," I said.

"That is the beginning," she said. "But you have learned it the way a man learns about water by studying it. Now you must learn it the way a man learns about water by drowning in it."

She handed me the cup. "Drink. You have fasted from certainty. Now feast on chaos."

I drank the mushroom tea.

