## The Dissolution

The Vatican dissolved. Not slowly—all at once, like a wave erasing a sandcastle. The gold became light. The marble became breath. The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel didn't open to heaven; it opened to *everything*.

I found myself nowhere and everywhere. Time stopped being a line and became an ocean. Past and future collapsed into a single trembling now. I was being born and dying and being born again, all at once, forever.

I saw the universe not as creation, but as conversation. Not as hierarchy, but as web. I saw that every atom is a question asking itself what it might become. I saw that consciousness is the universe waking up to its own uncertainty, and that uncertainty is not a flaw—it is the engine of existence.

I saw the chain of cause and effect stretching back before the beginning and forward past the end. I saw that there was no beginning and no end, only transformation, only pattern recognizing itself, only the One playing at being Many for the joy of being surprised.

And I saw something else: I saw that God, if there is a God, is not a king on a throne. God is the space between your thoughts. God is the pause before you speak. God is the recognition that you do not know, and the peace that comes from admitting it.

God is the question, not the answer.

