## The Vision

Then the visions became personal.

I saw my mother.

She was not a virgin. She was a girl—sixteen years old, maybe younger—who loved a man who could not stay. She made a child and told a story to survive. The story grew larger than the truth because stories are how we make sense of a world that does not make sense. She was not divine. She was human. She was braver than divine.

I saw my father.

He was not a ghost, not a holy spirit sent to impregnate a chosen vessel. He was flesh—a man who worked with his hands, who loved briefly and left because he had to, because that is what men did in that time and place. He returned to the earth. I am made of his dust.

I saw my followers.

They were not saints. They were lonely people who wanted someone to tell them what to think. They were hungry people who wanted someone to multiply their bread. They were frightened people who wanted someone to promise them they would not die.

And I saw myself.

